SIMPLE: ectype
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Ectype
<hw>Ec"type</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>ectype</ets>. See <er>Ectypal</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<fld>(Classical Arch⟦ae⟧ol.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A copy, as in
pottery, of an artist's original work. Hence:</def> <sd>(b)</sd> <def>A
work sculptured in relief, as a cameo, or in bas-relief (in this sense
used loosely).</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A copy from an original; a type of something that
has previously existed.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Some regarded him [Klopstock] as an <qex>ectype</qex> of the
ancient prophets.</q> <rj><qau>Eng. Cyc. .</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ectypography</ent>⟦br⟧
